'''Gonçalo Bernardo Inácio''' ({{IPA|pt|ɡõˈsalu iˈnasju}}; born 25 August 2001) is a Portuguese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for [[Primeira Liga]] club [[Sporting CP]] and the [[Portugal national football team|Portugal national team]].

Coming through [[Sporting CP]]'s youth academy, he made his first-team debut in 2020. He went on to win three [[Primeira Liga]] titles with the club in the [[2020–21 Primeira Liga|2020–21]], [[2023–24 Primeira Liga|2023–24]] and [[2024–25 Primeira Liga|2024–25 seasons]] (being named to the [[2023–24 Primeira Liga#Annual awards|2024]] and [[2024–25 Primeira Liga#Annual awards|2025 Teams of the Year]]), as well as back-to-back [[Taça da Liga|Taças da Liga]] in [[2020–21 Taça da Liga|2021]] and [[2021–22 Taça da Liga|2022]].

Having also been a [[Portugal national youth football team|Portugal youth international]], Inácio made his [[Portugal national football team|full]] debut in 2023, being part of the squad at [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]] and the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026 World Cup]]. He won the [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League]].

==Early life==
Inácio was born in [[Almada]], [[Setúbal District]] and raised in [[Seixal]], a municipality located {{convert|34.2|km|mi|abbr=on}} away. Growing up, he would play football wherever he could on the streets or in his house, and regularly attended [[Sporting CP]] matches with his father.<ref name=Dog>{{cite news|url=https://www.dn.pt/desporto/ja-nao-consigo-ir-passear-o-cao-a-rua-sem-se-juntar-uma-multidao-13772003.html|title="Já não consigo ir passear o cão à rua sem se juntar uma multidão"|trans-title="I can no longer walk the dog without gathering a crowd"|newspaper=[[Diário de Notícias]]|first=Isaura|last=Almeida|language=pt|date=27 May 2021|access-date=1 November 2021}}</ref>

Despite not having a particular idol, Inácio looked to emulate [[Jérémy Mathieu]].<ref name=Dog/>

==Club career==
[[File:Gonçalo Inácio 2021.png|thumb|upright|left|Inácio with [[Sporting CP]] in 2021]]
Inácio began his career at local [[Almada A.C.|Almada]], before moving to [[Sporting CP (youth)|Sporting's academy]]. Prior to this, he had several trials with crosstown rivals [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]], but ultimately decided not to join them when his father's car broke down on two occasions when he was being taken to training.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-betclic/sporting/detalhe/inacio-e-as-duas-avarias-que-o-tiraram-do-benfica-tambem-nao-gostava-de-estar-la|title=Inácio e as duas avarias que o 'tiraram'... do Benfica: "Também não gostava de estar lá"|trans-title=Inacio and the two breakdowns that 'took him' ... from Benfica: "I didn't like to be there either"|newspaper=[[Record (Portuguese newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=9 December 2021|access-date=20 May 2025}}</ref> On 13 January 2018, he signed his first professional contract at the age of 16.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-betclic/sporting/detalhe/goncalo-inacio-assinou-contrato-profissional|title=Gonçalo Inácio assinou contrato profissional|trans-title=Gonçalo Inácio signed a professional contract|newspaper=Record|first=André|last=Ferreira|language=pt|date=13 January 2018|access-date=20 May 2025}}</ref>

Inácio had his first call-up to the first team on 6 July 2020, remaining unused in a goalless draw at [[Moreirense F.C.|Moreirense]] in the [[Primeira Liga]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/sporting/noticias/muitas-novidades-no-onze-do-sporting-para-o-jogo-com-o-moreirense-12393392.html|title=Muitas novidades no onze do Sporting para o jogo com o Moreirense|trans-title=Many new faces in Sporting's XI for the game with Moreirense|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=pt|date=6 July 2020|access-date=8 January 2021}}</ref> he would initially struggle to be integrated, due to being reserved by nature, but managed to succeed with the help of manager [[Ruben Amorim]] and his teammates [[Nuno Mendes (footballer, born 2002)|Nuno Mendes]], [[Eduardo Quaresma]] and [[Tiago Tomás]], whom he had befriended during his time in the youth sides.<ref name=Dog/> He made his debut in a 2–0 away win against [[Portimonense S.C.|Portimonense]] on 4 October, as a 62nd-minute [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Zouhair Feddal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-betclic/sporting/detalhe/inacio-com-estreia-impetuosa|title=Inácio com estreia impetuosa|trans-title=Inácio with fiery debut|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=6 October 2020|access-date=20 May 2025}}</ref>

On 20 March 2021, Inácio scored his first goal, heading home from close range in the 1–0 home victory over [[Vitória S.C.|Vitória de Guimarães]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2021/03/20/desporto/noticia/sporting-vence-v-guimaraes-segura-10-pontos-vantagem-1955305|title=Sporting subiu mais um degrau|trans-title=Sporting further up the ladder|newspaper=[[Público (Portugal)|Público]]|first=David|last=Andrade|language=pt|date=20 March 2021|access-date=22 March 2021}}</ref> On 23 January, he provided the [[Assist (association football)|assist]] for [[Pedro Porro]] in a 1–0 defeat of [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] to help his club [[2021 Taça da Liga final|win]] the [[Taça da Liga]]; his performance in the match impressed Amorim, with the player eventually surpassing [[Luís Neto]] in the pecking order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.noticiasaominuto.com/desporto/1681619/goncalo-inacio-convence-ruben-amorim-e-espreita-nova-oportunidade|title=Gonçalo Inácio convence Rúben Amorim e espreita nova oportunidade|trans-title=Gonçalo Inácio convinces Rúben Amorim and waits for new chance|publisher=Notícias ao Minuto|first=Carlos|last=Pereira Fernandes|language=pt|date=4 February 2021|access-date=31 October 2021}}</ref> He played 20 times in the [[2020–21 Primeira Liga|domestic league]] for the eventual champions, ending a 19-year drought.<ref name=PL>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/2080-10-reasons-why-sporting-are-champions-of-portugal|title=10 reasons why Sporting are Champions of Portugal|publisher=PortuGOAL|first=Tom|last=Kundert|date=11 May 2021|access-date=25 May 2021}}</ref>

Inácio was named defender of the month for December 2021.<ref name=POTM>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-betclic/sporting/detalhe/goncalo-inacio-foi-o-melhor-jogador-jovem-em-novembro|title=Gonçalo Inácio foi o melhor jogador jovem em novembro|trans-title=Gonçalo Inácio was the best young player in November|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=17 December 2021|access-date=20 May 2025}}</ref> The following 29 January, his second-half header helped his team come from behind to defeat Benfica 2–1 in the [[2021 Taça da Liga Final|league cup final]].<ref name=LC>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/2426-sporting-defend-their-taca-da-liga-title-in-second-half-turnaround-versus-benfica|title=Sporting defend their Taça da Liga title in second-half turnaround versus Benfica|publisher=PortuGOAL|first=Patrick|last=Ribeiro|date=29 January 2022|access-date=30 January 2022}}</ref> On 1 April, he agreed to an extension until 2026.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sporting.pt/pt/noticias/futebol/equipa-principal/2022-04-01/goncalo-inacio-e-leao-ate-2026|title=Gonçalo Inácio é Leão até 2026|trans-title=Gonçalo Inácio a Lion until 2026|publisher=Sporting CP|language=pt|date=1 April 2022|access-date=10 April 2022}}</ref>

On 12 November 2023, in the [[Lisbon derby]] against Benfica at the [[Estádio da Luz]], Inácio was [[Fouls and misconduct (association football)|sent off]] after receiving a second yellow card at the start of the second half; Sporting went on to lose 2–1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsf.pt/desporto/benfica-sporting-relato-tsf-direto-i-liga-17326217.html|title=Há reviravoltas e depois há isto. Benfica vira e vence Sporting na compensação|trans-title=There are comebacks and then there is this. Benfica turn it around and beat Sporting in injury time|publisher=[[TSF (radio station)|TSF]]|first=Rui|last=Oliveira Costa|language=pt|date=12 November 2023|access-date=13 November 2023}}</ref> On 14 December, in their final [[UEFA Europa League]] [[2023–24 UEFA Europa League|group game]], at home to [[SK Sturm Graz|Sturm Graz]], he came off the bench at [[half-time]] and scored twice in ten minutes to seal a 3–0 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-betclic/sporting/detalhe/um-bis-em-10-minutos-goncalo-inacio-apanhou-lhe-o-jeito-diante-do-sturm-graz|title=Um bis em 10 minutos: Gonçalo Inácio apanhou-lhe o jeito diante do Sturm Graz|trans-title=A brace in 10 minutes: Gonçalo Inácio got the hang of it against Sturm Graz|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=14 December 2023|access-date=14 December 2023}}</ref> During [[2023–24 Primeira Liga|the season]], he contributed 32 appearances and nearly 2,500 minutes as the club own its 20th league,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvi.iol.pt/noticias/liga/sporting/sporting-29-campeoes-entre-eles-quatro-guarda-redes-e-um-jogador-despromovido|title=Sporting: 29 campeões, entre eles quatro guarda-redes e um jogador... despromovido|trans-title=Sporting: 29 champions, including four goalkeepers and a... relegated player|publisher=[[Televisão Independente]]|language=pt|date=19 May 2024|access-date=31 October 2024}}</ref> being consequently included in the [[2023–24 Primeira Liga#Annual awards|Team of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/primeira-liga/artigos/jota-silva-fecha-o-onze-do-ano-da-primeira-liga|title=Jota Silva fecha o 'Onze do Ano' da Primeira Liga|trans-title=Jota Silva completes the First League's 'All-Star Team'|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=pt|date=13 June 2024|access-date=31 October 2024}}</ref>

Inácio made his 200th competitive appearance on 23 February 2025, in a 2–2 away draw against [[AVS Futebol SAD|AVS]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/3389712709/goncalo-inacio-homenageado-pelos-200-jogos-no-sporting/|title=Gonçalo Inácio homenageado pelos 200 jogos no Sporting|trans-title=Gonçalo Inácio honoured for 200 games at Sporting|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=4 March 2025|access-date=9 March 2025}}</ref> He totalled six goals for [[2024–25 Primeira Liga|the campaign]] (three in the league), again claiming the national championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://observador.pt/2025/05/17/quem-sao-os-34-novos-campeoes-pelo-sporting-em-2024-25-e-o-que-fizeram-ao-longo-da-epoca/|title=Quem são os 34 novos campeões pelo Sporting em 2024/25 (e o que fizeram ao longo da época)|trans-title=Who are the 34 new champions for Sporting in 2024/25 (and what did they do throughout the season)|newspaper=[[Observador]]|first=Bruno|last=Roseiro|language=pt|date=17 May 2025|access-date=20 May 2025}}</ref>

On 11 December 2025, Inácio renewed his contract until June 2030.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sporting.pt/pt/noticias/futebol/equipa-principal/2025-12-11/goncalo-inacio-renova-ate-2030|title=Gonçalo Inácio renova até 2030|trans-title=Gonçalo Inácio renews until 2030|publisher=Sporting CP|language=pt|date=11 December 2025|access-date=11 December 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Tigran Barseghyan and Gonçalo Inácio 2229.jpg|thumb|Inácio with [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in 2025]]
Inácio represented [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] at [[Portugal national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[Portugal national under-18 football team|under-18]], [[Portugal national under-19 football team|under-19]], [[Portugal national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[Portugal national under-21 football team|under-21 levels]], for a total of 19 [[Cap (sport)|caps]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribunaexpresso.pt/selecao/2021-08-30-Goncalo-Inacio-dispensado-da-selecao-devido-a-problemas-fisicos-12f1bde5|title=Gonçalo Inácio dispensado da seleção devido a problemas físicos|trans-title=Gonçalo Inácio released by the national team due to physical problems|newspaper=[[Expresso (newspaper)|Expresso]]|language=pt|date=30 August 2021|access-date=31 October 2021}}</ref> He was called up to the senior side by [[Fernando Santos (footballer, born 1954)|Fernando Santos]] on 26 August 2021, for [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifiers]] against [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]] and the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] with [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rtp.pt/noticias/selecao-nacional/otavio-e-goncalo-inacio-convocados-por-fernando-santos_d1344591|title=Otávio e Gonçalo Inácio convocados por Fernando Santos|trans-title=Otávio and Gonçalo Inácio called by Fernando Santos|publisher=[[Rádio e Televisão de Portugal]]|first=Mário|last=Aleixo|language=pt|date=26 August 2021|access-date=31 October 2021}}</ref> Four days later, however, he was dropped from the squad after picking up an injury on his left thigh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/selecao-nacional/30-08-2021/selecao-goncalo-inacio-dispensado-por-lesao|title=Seleção: Gonçalo Inácio dispensado por lesão|trans-title=National team: Gonçalo Inácio released due to injury|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=30 August 2021|access-date=4 November 2021}}</ref>

On 12 November 2021, Inácio made his under-21 debut, playing the entire 1–0 win in [[Cyprus national under-21 football team|Cyprus]] in the [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2023 UEFA European Championship]] [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|qualifying stage]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2021/11/12/desporto/noticia/portugal-embalado-magia-vitinha-eficacia-ramos-1984749|title=Portugal embalado pela magia de Vitinha e a eficácia de Ramos|trans-title=Portugal propelled by Vitinha magic and Ramos efficiency|newspaper=Público|language=pt|date=12 November 2021|access-date=16 November 2021}}</ref> He scored his first goal in the reverse fixture four days later, in a 6–0 rout in [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rr.sapo.pt/bola-branca/noticia/clube-portugal/2021/11/16/portugal-goleia-chipre-e-lidera-corrida-ao-euro-sub-21/261011/|title=Portugal goleia Chipre e lidera corrida ao Euro sub-21|trans-title=Portugal rout Cyprus and lead under-21 Euro race|publisher=[[Rádio Renascença]]|language=pt|date=16 November 2021|access-date=16 November 2021}}</ref>

In October 2022, Inácio was named in a preliminary 55-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/selecoes/detalhe/cmtv-revela-lista-de-pre-convocados-para-o-mundial2022-conheca-todos-os-nomes?ref=HP_DestaquesPrincipais|title=A lista de pré-convocados da Seleção para o Mundial'2022: conheça todos os nomes|trans-title=The pre-selected for the 2022 World Cup: know all the names|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=23 October 2022|access-date=31 October 2022}}</ref> His first appearance took place on 23 March 2023, when he played the entire 4–0 victory over [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying|qualifiers]] which was the first game in charge of new manager [[Roberto Martínez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/selecao/3146-ronaldo-at-the-double-as-portugal-beat-liechtenstein-4-0-in-the-euro-2024-qualifiers|title=Ronaldo at the double as Portugal beat Liechtenstein 4–0 in the Euro 2024 qualifiers|publisher=PortuGOAL|first=Matthew|last=Marshall|date=23 March 2023|access-date=23 March 2023}}</ref> On 11 September, still during that stage, he scored his first and second goals in a 9–0 home defeat of [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]], Portugal's biggest win in international history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/portugal/selecao-nacional/portugal-9-0-luxemburgo-cronica|title=Portugal 9–0 Luxemburgo (crónica)|trans-title=Portugal 9–0 Luxembourg (report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|first=Pedro|last=Lemos|language=pt|date=11 September 2023|access-date=11 September 2023}}</ref>

Inácio was selected for the Euro 2024 finals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5509185/2024/05/21/portugal-euro-2024-squad/|title=Portugal’s Euro 2024 squad: Pedro Neto one of nine Premier League players included, Matheus Nunes left out|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|first=Tim|last=Spiers|date=21 May 2024|access-date=21 May 2024}}</ref> In the team's opening match against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]], he replaced [[Diogo Dalot]] in the 63rd minute of the 2–1 comeback win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c3ggyn075p8t|title=Portugal 2–1 Czech Republic|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|first=Gary|last=Rose|date=18 June 2024|access-date=7 July 2024}}</ref> He also featured 90 minutes of the final [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group F|group]] fixture, a 2–0 loss to [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cqllllkd73dt|title=Georgia 2–0 Portugal|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Adam|last=Millington|date=26 June 2024|access-date=7 July 2024}}</ref> in a quarter-final elimination against [[France national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy79llev4znt|title=Portugal 0–0 France (France win 5–3 on pens)|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Emma|last=Sanders|date=5 July 2024|access-date=7 July 2024}}</ref>

On 20 May 2025, Inácio was included in Martínez's squad for the upcoming [[2025 UEFA Nations League Finals|UEFA Nations League Finals]] to be held in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fpf.pt/pt/News/Todas-as-notícias/Notícia/news/50645|title=Convocatória para Liga das Nações divulgada|trans-title=Nations League squad announced|publisher=[[Portuguese Football Federation]]|language=pt|date=20 May 2025|access-date=14 June 2025}}</ref> He started twice for the champions, including in the 5–3 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] defeat of [[Spain national football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cj6rw18xk1yt|title=Germany 1–2 Portugal|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Michael|last=Emons|date=4 June 2025|access-date=14 June 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6408339/2025/06/08/spain-portugal-yamal-mendes-ronaldo/|title=Spain 2 Portugal 2 (3–5 on pens): Mendes vs Yamal, Ronaldo being Ronaldo, and World Cup chances|newspaper=The New York Times|first=Tim|last1=Spiers|first2=Dermot|last2=Corrigan|first3=Stu|last3=James|date=8 June 2025|access-date=14 June 2025}}</ref>

Inácio was also picked for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/2026/05/19/the-reason-portugal-called-up-4-goalkeepers-for-world-cup-reason-to-fret-for-cristiano-ronaldo-fans.html|title=The reason Portugal called up 4 goalkeepers for World Cup: No reason to fret for Cristiano Ronaldo fans|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|first=Matias|last=Wodner|date=19 May 2026|access-date=1 June 2026}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Inácio has been predominantly deployed as a central defender, but can also play as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left-back]] and a [[midfielder]] due to his attributes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-betclic/sporting/detalhe/ruben-amorim-inspira-se-em-guardiola-goncalo-inacio-foi-medio-com-o-maritimo|title=Rúben Amorim inspira-se em Guardiola: Gonçalo Inácio foi médio com o Marítimo|trans-title=Rúben Amorim takes inspiration from Guardiola: Gonçalo Inácio played midfielder with Marítimo|newspaper=Record|first1=João|last1=Soares Ribeiro|first2=Ricardo|last2=Granada|language=pt|date=16 July 2023|access-date=2 November 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/taca-da-liga/artigos/ruben-amorim-comenta-interesse-do-manchester-united-gyokeres-feliz-pelo-hat-trick|title=Rúben Amorim comenta interesse do Manchester United, Gyokeres feliz pelo hat-trick|trans-title=Rúben Amorim talks about Manchester United interest, Gyokeres happy with hat-trick|publisher=SAPO|language=pt|date=2 November 2023|access-date=2 November 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnportugal.iol.pt/videos/ruben-amorim-explica-goncalo-inacio-no-meio-campo/65442aeb0cf23250d70e79bc|title=Ruben Amorim explica Gonçalo Inácio no meio-campo|trans-title=Ruben Amorim explains Gonçalo Inácio in midfield|publisher=[[CNN Portugal]]|language=pt|date=2 November 2023|access-date=2 November 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://observador.pt/programas/relat-rio-de-jogo/goncalo-inacio-a-medio-e-boa-aposta-de-amorim/|title="Gonçalo Inácio a médio é boa aposta de Amorim"|trans-title="Gonçalo Inácio at midfielder is a good bet by Amorim"|newspaper=Observador|first=Mário|last=Cagica|language=pt|date=2 November 2023|access-date=2 November 2023}}</ref> He is noted for his anticipation, composure, decisions, positioning, tackling and passing ability, including long-range passes which enables him to break down attacks and subsequently play the ball out or start offensive plays from the back, as well as for his acceleration, agility and pace.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-betclic/sporting/detalhe/inteligencia-artificial-coloca-goncalo-inacio-entre-os-melhores-jovens-centrais-da-europa|title=Inteligência Artificial coloca Gonçalo Inácio entre os melhores jovens centrais da Europa|trans-title=Artificial Intelligence puts Gonçalo Inácio amongst Europe's best young stoppers|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=18 February 2022|access-date=16 August 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foottheball.com/players-in-focus/goncalo-inacio-stats-profile-sporting-scout-report-transfer-news-analysis-potential/|title=Goncalo Inacio: Nicknamed 'The Portuguese Boss' – He's the next big defensive transfer target for elite clubs|publisher=Foot The Ball|first=Arnold|last=Lewis|date=18 August 2022|access-date=16 August 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abola.pt/nnh/2023-07-19/sporting-o-novo-goncalo-inacio-e-um-menino-destemido-a-analise-ao-leao/997115|title=Sporting-Genk: Análise individual e jogadores em destaque|trans-title=Sporting-Genk: Individual analysis and highlighted players|newspaper=[[A Bola]]|first=Rui|last=Baioneta|language=pt|date=19 July 2023|access-date=17 August 2023}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Inácio was a Sporting fan since he was a child, and his brother Rodrigo was born with a [[disability]]. The former considered himself a shy person who did not feel comfortable posting about himself on [[social media]]; his favourite hobbies were playing [[Street football (association football)|street football]] and the [[PlayStation]] alone or with friends.<ref name=Dog/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/primeira-liga/artigos/goncalo-inacio-queria-era-ser-guarda-redes-mas-o-meu-pai-nao-deixou|title=Gonçalo Inácio: "Queria era ser guarda-redes mas o meu pai não deixou"|trans-title=Gonçalo Inácio: "What I really wanted to be was a goalkeeper but my father did not let me"|publisher=SAPO|language=pt|date=10 December 2021|access-date=3 November 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oLHHmuYNOlE|title=ADN de Leão {{!}} Episódio 48: Gonçalo Inácio|trans-title=Lion DNA {{!}} Episode 48: Gonçalo Inácio|publisher=[[YouTube]]|language=pt|access-date=28 September 2023}}</ref>

